@@eMafdet: The Guardian Port@@N

At the eastern edge of the Saltglass Reach, where the inland desert meets
the open sea, stands @@yMafdet@@N -- the fortified beach harbor that serves as
the world's gateway between land and ocean. The city takes its name from
a protective figure invoked in pre-Keeper coastal rituals: a swift, feline
executioner who punished oath-breakers and those who preyed on the
defenseless. The name carries an implicit promise: justice here is swift,
precise, and unsentimental.

@@yThe Guardian Tradition@@N

Every citizen of Mafdet carries a @@yguardian-name@@N alongside their given name,
a tradition inherited from the ancient watch cults. The guardian-name is
not a title of rank but a covenant of accountability -- it marks the bearer
as one who has sworn, in the guardian's sight, to uphold the port's trust.
The Shrine of the First Claw, positioned between harbor and ledger quarter,
is where trade oaths are sealed upon a basalt claw worn smooth by centuries
of hands. Breaking an oath sealed at the First Claw is the most serious
commercial crime in the city.

@@gDual Attestation@@N

No cargo enters or leaves Mafdet without verification under both inland and
maritime standards -- the @@gdual-attestation protocol@@N. Inland provenance must
be certified against oasis charter formulas; maritime risk must be assessed
against harbor precedent. This is the Shoreward Conversion made permanent:
the beach is a legal boundary where two kinds of law are reconciled.

@@dThe Ledger Houses@@N

Four Ledger Houses form the commercial brain of the port. The @@yTide Ledger
Hall@@N certifies bulk commodities against the Saltweight standard. The
@@eShoreward House@@N employs bilingual legal clerks trained in both oasis
charter and maritime notation. The @@lStorm Ledger@@N handles insurance, escrow,
and weather advisories. The @@rQuarantine Ledger@@N -- smallest but most sensitive
-- classifies pyramid-origin artifacts by hazard level, determining what may
be exported and what must be held, destroyed, or returned.

@@rThe Quarantine Ledger@@N

The Quarantine Ledger's Hazard Scribes are trained in inland relic provenance
and maritime containment assessment. Their four-tier classification descends
from Khar'Daan's ancient funerary-bureaucratic containment system. In a
meaningful sense, the Quarantine Ledger's scribes are Khar'Daan's last
functioning bureaucrats.

@@lThe Strandline Compact@@N

Three operational blocs share power: @@lHarbor Wardens@@N enforce quay security,
the harbor chain, and anti-piracy watch. @@yLedger Houses@@N certify manifests
and conversion documentation. The @@dSand-Sea Carters' Guild@@N controls overland
linkage to the oasis corridors. Wardens need guild throughput, guilds need
ledger legitimacy, and ledgers need warden enforcement. No bloc dominates
for long.

The harbor's bronze signal towers are the first thing arriving ships see,
and the Shrine's claw-marked spire the second. Between them, Mafdet
processes the traffic of civilizations with brisk efficiency: it pays
fairly, heals without prejudice, and never asks where you came from --
only what you can carry.
